    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nCommand line with ui2 can start looking like a regular window. Probably a result of #25185. Maybe it can have wider effect.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. `nvim --clean`\n2. `:set number`\n3. `:lua require('vim._core.ui2').enable({ enable = true })`\n4. `:tabedit`. The command line now shows line numbers.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nCommand line view does not depend on option values for regular windows.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.12.0-dev-2459+g62135f5a57\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nNo, doesn't have this functionality\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nEndeavourOS Linux x86_64, 6.18.13-arch1-1\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nGhostty 1.2.3-arch3\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-ghostty\n\n### Installation\n\nAppimage",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "`nvim_win_get_config` doesn't return `style = \"minimal\"` if it was set, so I guess this ends up resetting the style:\n\nhttps://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/563f9ef7994a35686419b4524cd772c97960dac1/runtime/lua/vim/_core/ui2.lua#L91\n\nDunno if there was a specific reason why `nvim_win_get_config` does that. Maybe a bug. I'll open a PR anyways.",
